<!-- Parallel Lines [pg4] -->
<div data-role="page" id="ParallelLines" data-theme="c">
<div data-role="header" data-position="fixed">
<a href="javascript:history.go(-1)" data-transition="fade">Back</a>
<h1>Parallel Lines</h1>
<a href="#AboutGeom" data-transition="fade">About</a>
</div><!-- /header -->

<div data-role="content">
<article> 
<img class="page" src="imagesPg4/illusion.jpg" width="150" height="100" alt="Parallel Illusion">

<div data-role="collapsible-set">

<div data-role="collapsible">
<h3>Parallels and Transversals</h3>
<img class="page" src="imagesPg4/transversal2.jpg" width="240" height="175" alt="Parallel and Transversal">
<p class="instruction">
Parallel lines are lines in a plane that do not intersect even when extended. A third line that crosses parallels is called a transversal. This divides the plane into three areas - above and below the parallels [exterior] and between them [interior.]</p>

<img class="page" src="imagesPg4/transversal.jpg" width="240" height="175" alt="Parallel and Transversal">
<p class="instruction">

</p>
</div><!-- /collapse -->

<div data-role="collapsible">
<h3>Transversals and Angles</h3>
<img class="page" src="imagesPg4/angles.jpg" width="217" height="208" alt="Transversal and Angles">
<p class="instruction">
A transversal crossing parallel lines creates 8 angles which have "pair" names: alternate interior angles - &#8736;4, &#8736;6 and &#8736;3, &#8736;5; alternate exterior angles - &#8736;1, &#8736;7 and &#8736;2, &#8736;8; corresponding angles - &#8736;1, &#8736;5 and &#8736;2, &#8736;6 and &#8736;3, &#8736;7 and &#8736;4, &#8736;8.</p>
<p class="instruction">
ALTERNATE INTERIOR ANGLES ARE EQUAL; 
ALTERNATE EXTERIOR ANGLES ARE EQUAL; 
CORRESPONDING ANGLES ARE EQUAL</p>
<img class="page" src="imagesPg4/eqangles.jpg" width="145" height="169" alt="Transversal and Equal Angle Pairs">
</div><!-- /collapse -->

<div data-role="collapsible">
<h3>Other Parallelisms</h3>
<img class="page" src="imagesPg4/stepladder.png" width="106" height="127" alt="Step Ladder">
<p class="instruction">
LINES PARALLEL TO A THIRD LINE ARE PARALLEL; 
LINES PERPENDICULAR TO A THIRD LINE ARE PARALLEL.<br>
In a step ladder, each step is parallel to the step immediately below it and the bottom step is parallel to the floor. Yardlines on a football field are parallel and perpendicular to the sidelines.
</p>
<img class="page" src="imagesPg4/football.jpg" width="170" height="113" alt="Football Field">

</div><!-- /collapse -->


<div data-role="collapsible">
<h3>The Parallel Postulate</h3>
<img class="page" src="imagesPg4/parapost.jpg" width="240" height="200" alt="Parallel Postulate">
<p class="instruction">
Euclid correctly postulated [meaning it cannot be proved] that only one line can pass through a point and be parallel to a given line. Contrary assumptions lead to alternate valid and consistent geometries.</p>
<img src="imagesPg4/altgeo1.jpg" width="240" height="250" alt="Euclidean Geometry">
<img src="imagesPg4/altgeo2.jpg" width="240" height="250" alt="Elliptic Geometry">
<img src="imagesPg4/altgeo3.jpg" width="240" height="250" alt="Hyperbolic Geometry">
</div><!-- /collapse -->

<div data-role="collapsible">
<h3>Self Quiz</h3>
<ol>
<li>Name the angle pair.<br>
<img class="page" src="imagesPg4/corresp.jpg" width="175" height="160" alt="Corresponding Angles"></li>
<li>True or False?
<img class="page" src="imagesPg4/true.jpg" width="192" height="107" alt="Equal Alternate Interior Angles"></li>
<li>What geometry is suggested by the surface of a chip?<br><br>
<img class="page" src="imagesPg4/chips.jpg" width="200" height="146" alt="Potato Chips"></li>
</ol>
</div><!-- /collapse -->


<div data-role="collapsible">
<h3>Answers</h3>
<ol>
<li>corresponding angles</li>
<li>true</li>
<li>hyperbolic</li>
</ol>
</div><!-- /collapse -->
</div><!-- /collapsible set -->


</article>
</div><!-- /content -->

